'''Mihail Lozanov''' ({{lang-bg|<U+041C><U+0438><U+0445><U+0430><U+0438><U+043B> <U+041B><U+043E><U+0437><U+0430><U+043D><U+043E><U+0432>}}; 15 June 1911<U+2013>3 December 1994), nicknamed '''The Tank''' (<U+0422><U+0430><U+043D><U+043A><U+0430>, ''Tanka'') was a [[Bulgaria]]n [[association football|footballer]]. A [[centre forward]], Lozanov was a long-time player of [[PFC Levski Sofia]] in the 1930s and [[captain (association football)|captained]] [[FC Bayern Munich]] in 1937<U+2013>39.

==Club career==
Born in the village of Tsarnel (today [[Lyulin, Pernik Province|Lyulin]]) near [[Pernik]] in 1911, Lozanov started playing football at [[PFC Minyor Pernik|SC Krakra Pernik]]<ref name="bgdnes">{{cite web|url=http://www.bgdnes.bg/Article.asp?Id=2013781|title=<U+0411><U+044A><U+043B><U+0433><U+0430><U+0440><U+0438><U+043D> <U+0432><U+043E><U+0434><U+0438> "<U+0411><U+0430><U+0439><U+0435><U+0440><U+043D>" <U+043F><U+043E> <U+0432><U+0440><U+0435><U+043C><U+0435><U+0442><U+043E> <U+043D><U+0430> <U+0425><U+0438><U+0442><U+043B><U+0435><U+0440>|date=2013-05-27|publisher=bgDNES.bg|language=Bulgarian|accessdate=12 April 2014}}</ref> at age nine. The club had been newly co-founded by his brother Todor Lozanov.<ref name="pernikonline">{{cite news|url=http://www.pernikonline.com/novini/pravyat-izlojba-za-futbolnata-legenda-mihail-lozanov-tanka|title=<U+041F><U+0440><U+0430><U+0432><U+044F><U+0442> <U+0438><U+0437><U+043B><U+043E><U+0436><U+0431><U+0430> <U+0437><U+0430> <U+0444><U+0443><U+0442><U+0431><U+043E><U+043B><U+043D><U+0430><U+0442><U+0430> <U+043B><U+0435><U+0433><U+0435><U+043D><U+0434><U+0430> <U+041C><U+0438><U+0445><U+0430><U+0438><U+043B> <U+041B><U+043E><U+0437><U+0430><U+043D><U+043E><U+0432>&nbsp;<U+2014> <U+0422><U+0430><U+043D><U+043A><U+0430>|date=2011-06-09|publisher=Pernik Online|language=Bulgarian|accessdate=12 April 2014}}</ref> When he moved to the capital [[Sofia]] to attend high school, he transferred to powerhouse [[PFC Levski Sofia]] in 1930, where he spent most of his career. At Levski, Lozanov formed a formidable attacking trio with teammates [[Asen Panchev]] and [[Asen Peshev]] and scored 43 goals in 79 league games.<ref name="bfu">{{cite news|url=http://www.bfunion.bg/news/314|title=<U+041D><U+0430><U+0432><U+044A><U+0440><U+0448><U+0432><U+0430><U+0442> <U+0441><U+0435> 98 <U+0433><U+043E><U+0434><U+0438><U+043D><U+0438> <U+043E><U+0442> <U+0440><U+043E><U+0436><U+0434><U+0435><U+043D><U+0438><U+0435><U+0442><U+043E> <U+043D><U+0430> <U+041C><U+0438><U+0445><U+0430><U+0438><U+043B> <U+041B><U+043E><U+0437><U+0430><U+043D><U+043E><U+0432>&nbsp;<U+2014> <U+0422><U+0430><U+043D><U+043A><U+0430>|date=2009-06-15|publisher=[[Bulgarian Football Union|<U+0411><U+044A><U+043B><U+0433><U+0430><U+0440><U+0441><U+043A><U+0438> <U+0444><U+0443><U+0442><U+0431><U+043E><U+043B><U+0435><U+043D> <U+0441><U+044A><U+044E><U+0437>]]|language=Bulgarian|accessdate=12 April 2014}}</ref> Lozanov's attacking prowess earned him the nickname The Tank; reportedly, he once shattered the bar with a powerful shot.<ref name="bgdnes"/> With Levski, Lozanov won the [[Bulgarian State Football Championship]] twice, in [[1933 Bulgarian State Football Championship|1933]] and [[1937 Bulgarian State Football Championship|1937]].<ref name="pernikonline"/> These were Levski's first two championship titles.<ref name="blitz">{{cite news|url=http://www.blitz.bg/article/28305|title=17 <U+0433><U+043E><U+0434><U+0438><U+043D><U+0438> <U+043E><U+0442> <U+0441><U+043C><U+044A><U+0440><U+0442><U+0442><U+0430> <U+043D><U+0430> <U+041C><U+0438><U+0445><U+0430><U+0438><U+043B> <U+041B><U+043E><U+0437><U+0430><U+043D><U+043E><U+0432>: <U+0422><U+0430><U+043D><U+043A><U+0430> <U+0431><U+0435> <U+043A><U+0430><U+043F><U+0438><U+0442><U+0430><U+043D> <U+043D><U+0430> <U+201C><U+0411><U+0430><U+0439><U+0435><U+0440><U+043D><U+201D> (<U+041C><U+044E><U+043D><U+0445><U+0435><U+043D>)|last=<U+041F><U+0430><U+0439><U+0442><U+0430><U+0448><U+0435><U+0432>|first=<U+0420><U+0443><U+043C><U+0435><U+043D>|date=2011-12-05|publisher=<U+0411><U+043B><U+0438><U+0446>|language=Bulgarian|accessdate=12 April 2014}}</ref>

As a student in [[Brno]], [[Czechoslovakia]] in 1935, Lozanov played for local side [[SK Moravsk<U+00E1> Slavia Brno|SK Moravsk<U+00E1> Slavia]]. Then, Lozanov moved to [[Munich]] in [[Nazi Germany]] to continue his education as a [[civil engineer]] at the [[Technische Universit<U+00E4>t M<U+00FC>nchen|Munich Polytechnic School]]. In Munich, Lozanov represented and captained FC Bayern Munich, the most successful club in German history.<ref name="bgdnes"/> Lozanov was a regular first team player in the [[Gauliga Bayern]] between 1937 and 1939, featuring for Bayern Munich alongside German internationals [[Ludwig Goldbrunner]], [[Jakob Streitle]] and [[Wilhelm Simetsreiter]].<ref name="pernikonline"/>

Returning to Bulgaria, Lozanov continued his career at Levski Sofia for two more years until retiring from football in 1941 at age 30. In his later years, he was a mining engineer in Pernik.<ref name="bgdnes"/>

==International career==
Mihail Lozanov was among the stars of the [[Bulgaria national football team]] in the 1930s. He debuted against [[Yugoslavia national football team|Yugoslavia]] in a 0<U+2013>1 loss in 1931 and played his last game against [[Germany national football team|Germany]] in a 1<U+2013>2 loss in 1939. In between, Lozanov won the [[Balkan Cup]] twice with Bulgaria, in [[1932 Balkan Cup|1932]] and [[1935 Balkan Cup|1935]].<ref name="bfu"/> He also took part in the [[1934 FIFA World Cup]] qualification cycle.<ref name="blitz"/><ref name="paytashev">{{cite book|last=<U+041F><U+0430><U+0439><U+0442><U+0430><U+0448><U+0435><U+0432>|first=<U+0420><U+0443><U+043C><U+0435><U+043D>|title=<U+0424><U+0443><U+0442><U+0431><U+043E><U+043B>: <U+0438><U+0441><U+0442><U+043E><U+0440><U+0438><U+044F> <U+043D><U+0430> <U+0441><U+0432><U+0435><U+0442><U+043E><U+0432><U+043D><U+0438><U+0442><U+0435> <U+043F><U+044A><U+0440><U+0432><U+0435><U+043D><U+0441><U+0442><U+0432><U+0430>|publisher=<U+0422><U+0440><U+0443><U+0434>|location=<U+0421><U+043E><U+0444><U+0438><U+044F>|pages=28|isbn=9789545286018|language=Bulgarian}}</ref> For the national team, Lozanov recorded a total of 38 caps and 10 goals.<ref name="bfu"/>

